AB  - This paper analyzes the effects of import controls on production and price formation in the Colombian manufacturing sector in 1976–1987. For that purpose, it presents and estimates a simple model of imperfect competition which captures the quantity and price effects of QRs. The statistical results support the idea that direct import controls have strong quantity and weak price effects. The former concentrate in a few sectors (particularly machinery and equipment), most of which are not sensible to relative import prices. However, even in sectors where QRs have weak direct quantity effects, indirect effects of import policy may be important, given the sensitivity of industrial production to aggregate demand.
